+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PbguX5ZVQR74MfN9QUDE6j","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the implementation. Let me compile my findings.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: FTS5 Full-Text Search Implementation\n\n**Commit**: `41905eb` (\"implementation\")\n**Files Reviewed**: `/workspace/src/db.ts`, `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, `/workspace/src/models.ts`, `/workspace/tests/search.test.ts`\n**Test Status**: All 35 tests passing.\n\n---\n\n### What Was Done Well\n\n- The FTS5 content-sync table pattern (`content='notes'`, `content_rowid='id'`) with insert/delete/update triggers is the canonical SQLite approach -- correctly implemented.\n- BM25 ranking and `snippet()` usage are idiomatic FTS5.\n- Parameterized queries throughout -- no raw string interpolation into SQL.\n- Inner `try/catch` blocks around FTS MATCH operations gracefully degrade invalid queries to empty results rather than 500 errors.\n- The test suite is comprehensive at 20 search-specific tests including CRUD-sync verification and special character handling.\n- Pagination implementation is clean and correct.\n\n---\n\n### HIGH Priority Findings\n\n**H1: FTS5 boolean operators (`NOT`, `OR`, `AND`, `NEAR`) pass through sanitization unmodified**\n\nFile: `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, lines 6-26\n\nThe `sanitizeFtsQuery` function strips special punctuation characters but preserves alphabetic tokens verbatim. FTS5 keywords like `NOT`, `OR`, `AND`, and `NEAR` are valid alphanumeric words and pass through completely intact. This creates several problematic scenarios:\n\n- Input `\"NOT\"` produces output `\"NOT\"` -- a bare `NOT` is invalid FTS5 syntax and will throw an error (caught by the inner try/catch, so it degrades to empty results rather than crashing, but it is a silent data-loss scenario where a user searching for the word \"not\" gets zero results).\n- Input `\"hello OR world\"` produces `\"hello OR world\"` -- this becomes a boolean OR query rather than an implicit AND across three tokens. A user typing natural text like \"salt or pepper\" would get a boolean disjunction instead of an AND search for all three words.\n- Input `\"hello NOT world\"` would exclude results containing \"world,\" which is almost certainly not what a user intends when typing natural language.\n- Input `\"NOT hello\"` is a negation-only query which may produce unexpected results or errors depending on FTS5 version.\n\nRecommendation: After cleaning each token, lowercase-compare it against FTS5 reserved keywords and either quote them or strip them:\n\n```typescript\nconst FTS5_KEYWORDS = new Set(['and', 'or', 'not', 'near']);\n\n// Inside the else-if branch for unquoted tokens:\nconst cleaned = match[2].replace(/[^\\w*]/g, '');\nif (cleaned) {\n  if (FTS5_KEYWORDS.has(cleaned.toLowerCase())) {\n    // Quote the keyword so FTS5 treats it as a literal term\n    parts.push(`\"${cleaned}\"`);\n  } else {\n    parts.push(cleaned);\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**H2: Bare `*` (wildcard-only) query can match every row in the FTS index**\n\nFile: `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, line 18\n\nThe sanitizer preserves `*` since the regex `[^\\w*]` explicitly allows it. Input `\"*\"` produces output `\"*\"`, and input `\"***\"` produces output `\"***\"`. In FTS5, a bare `*` as a prefix token is undefined behavior -- depending on the SQLite version it may match all documents or throw an error. Either way, it is not a meaningful search.\n\nRecommendation: After cleaning, reject tokens that consist entirely of asterisks, or strip trailing asterisks from the sanitized output (and only allow `*` from the suggest endpoint where prefix search is intentional):\n\n```typescript\nconst cleaned = match[2].replace(/[^\\w*]/g, '');\n// Reject pure-wildcard tokens\nif (cleaned && cleaned.replace(/\\*/g, '').length > 0) {\n  parts.push(cleaned);\n}\n```\n\n**H3: Special characters inside quoted phrases are not sanitized**\n\nFile: `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, line 15\n\nWhen the regex matches a quoted phrase (`match[1]`), the inner content is re-wrapped in quotes verbatim. The edge-case analysis confirms that input `\"content with special!@#$\"` produces output `\"content with special!@#$\"` unchanged. While FTS5 is generally tolerant of special characters inside quotes, certain characters (particularly `\"` itself if nested) can break the query syntax. The test confirmed that input `\" OR \"\" = \"` produces `\" OR \" \" = \"` -- a malformed FTS5 expression with unbalanced quotes.\n\nRecommendation: Sanitize the inner content of quoted phrases as well, at minimum stripping any embedded double-quote characters:\n\n```typescript\nif (match[1] !== undefined) {\n  const innerCleaned = match[1].replace(/\"/g, '');\n  if (innerCleaned.trim()) {\n    parts.push(`\"${innerCleaned}\"`);\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### MEDIUM Priority Findings\n\n**M1: Suggest endpoint allows FTS5 boolean operators as prefix searches**\n\nFile: `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, line 119\n\nThe suggest sanitizer uses a simpler approach: `q.trim().replace(/[^\\w\\s]/g, '') + '*'`. This strips punctuation but preserves whitespace and alphabetic characters. Input `\"OR NOT\"` becomes `\"OR NOT*\"`, which is an FTS5 boolean expression meaning \"OR (any token starting with NOT).\" This is nonsensical and may throw or return unexpected results.\n\nSimilarly, input `\"hello world\"` becomes `\"hello world*\"`, where FTS5 interprets this as an implicit AND of `hello` and the prefix `world*`. While arguably reasonable for autocomplete, the behavior with internal whitespace creating multi-token MATCH queries may surprise users and differs from the search endpoint's semantics.\n\nRecommendation: Apply the same FTS5 keyword quoting from H1 to the suggest sanitizer, and consider taking only the last whitespace-delimited token for prefix matching.\n\n**M2: `perPage` is hardcoded with no upper-bound validation on `page`**\n\nFile: `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, lines 64-66\n\nWhile `page` is floored at 1 via `Math.max(1, ...)`, there is no upper bound. A request with `page=999999999` will compute `offset = (999999999 - 1) * 20 = 19999999960`, which SQLite will happily process (returning zero results), but it is wasted computation. More importantly, `perPage` is hardcoded to 20 with no way for the client to control it -- which is fine for now but worth noting if the API is expected to be flexible.\n\nRecommendation: Consider capping `page` at a reasonable maximum or computing it from `total`, and optionally accepting a `perPage` query parameter with min/max bounds.\n\n**M3: Two separate queries (COUNT then SELECT) for search pagination are not atomic**\n\nFile: `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, lines 73-97\n\nThe count query and the search query execute as two separate statements. If a concurrent write occurs between them (insert/delete), the `total` count can be inconsistent with the actual results returned. With `better-sqlite3` being synchronous this is less of a concern in practice (no true concurrency within a single connection), but if the application ever moves to a connection pool or WAL readers, this could manifest.\n\nRecommendation: Acceptable for current architecture, but if consistency becomes important, wrap both queries in a read transaction or use a `window COUNT(*) OVER()` approach in a single query.\n\n**M4: Route ordering -- `/notes/search` and `/notes/search/suggest` must be defined before `/notes/:id`**\n\nFile: `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, lines 56-157\n\nThe search routes are correctly placed before the `/:id` route in the current code. However, this ordering dependency is implicit and fragile. If anyone reorders routes during a future refactor, `/notes/search` would be captured by `/:id` with `id = \"search\"`, causing a `parseInt` to return `NaN` and a confusing 404.\n\nRecommendation: Add a comment documenting the ordering requirement, or validate that `:id` is a numeric string in the `/:id` handler.\n\n---\n\n### LOW Priority Findings\n\n**L1: Fallback to `\"\"` (empty quoted string) on empty/all-special-character input**\n\nFile: `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, line 25\n\nWhen sanitization strips all characters (e.g., input `\"----\"`), the function returns `\"\"` (an FTS5 empty quoted string). This will match zero rows, which is the correct behavior. However, it would be slightly cleaner to short-circuit and return empty results before even executing the MATCH query, avoiding unnecessary database round-trips.\n\n**L2: `snippet()` column index is hardcoded to `1` (body)**\n\nFile: `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, line 88\n\n```sql\nsnippet(notes_fts, 1, '<mark>', '</mark>', '...', 32) as snippet\n```\n\nThe column index `1` corresponds to `body` (the second column in the FTS5 table definition: `title` = 0, `body` = 1). If a user searches for a term that appears only in the title, the snippet will come from the body column and may not contain a highlighted match -- it could just show `...` ellipsis. This may confuse users who see a result listed but no highlighted text in the snippet.\n\nRecommendation: Consider using column index `-1` to let FTS5 choose the best column for the snippet, or generate snippets for both title and body.\n\n**L3: The `<mark>` HTML tags in snippets are not escaped/sanitized for XSS if rendered client-side**\n\nFile: `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, line 88\n\nThe snippet output contains raw `<mark>` and `</mark>` tags. If the original note content contains HTML (e.g., `<script>alert(1)</script>`), that HTML will appear in the snippet output unescaped. While this is an API (not a rendered page), any frontend consuming this API must sanitize the snippet before inserting it into the DOM. This is standard practice but worth documenting in API docs.\n\n**L4: Prepared statements are created inside route handlers on every request**\n\nFile: `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, lines 73, 84, 123\n\nEach call to `db.prepare(...)` parses and compiles the SQL statement. While `better-sqlite3` is fast at this and the overhead is small, it is more idiomatic to prepare statements once at router creation time and reuse them. This is how the CRUD routes in the existing codebase also work (they do the same thing, so this is consistent with the project's pattern, just noting it as a general optimization opportunity).\n\n**L5: No test for multi-word suggest queries or suggest with FTS5 operator keywords**\n\nFile: `/workspace/tests/search.test.ts`\n\nThe test suite covers single-prefix suggest queries well but does not test edge cases like `q=OR`, `q=hello world`, or `q=*` for the suggest endpoint. Given the issues noted in M1, adding these tests would catch regressions.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| ID | Priority | Category | Description |\n|----|----------|----------|-------------|\n| H1 | HIGH | Security/Correctness | FTS5 boolean operators (NOT, OR, AND, NEAR) pass through sanitization |\n| H2 | HIGH | Correctness | Bare `*` wildcard query can match all rows or produce undefined behavior |\n| H3 | HIGH | Security | Special characters inside quoted phrases are not sanitized |\n| M1 | MEDIUM | Correctness | Suggest endpoint passes FTS5 operators through to MATCH |\n| M2 | MEDIUM | Robustness | No upper bound on `page` parameter |\n| M3 | MEDIUM | Consistency | COUNT and SELECT for pagination are not atomic |\n| M4 | MEDIUM | Maintainability | Route ordering dependency is implicit and fragile |\n| L1 | LOW | Performance | Empty-string fallback still executes a MATCH query |\n| L2 | LOW | UX | Snippet hardcoded to body column; title-only matches show no highlight |\n| L3 | LOW | Security | `<mark>` snippet output is not HTML-escaped for downstream consumers |\n| L4 | LOW | Performance | Prepared statements recreated per request |\n| L5 | LOW | Testing | Missing edge-case tests for suggest endpoint |\n\nThe three HIGH issues (H1, H2, H3) all relate to the `sanitizeFtsQuery` function in `/workspace/src/routes.ts` lines 6-26. They share a common root cause: the sanitizer was designed to strip punctuation-based FTS5 operators but does not account for keyword-based operators or content inside quoted phrases. A focused revision of that single function -- plus a parallel fix to the suggest sanitizer on line 119 -- would address all three HIGH and the M1 MEDIUM finding."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ac2a0b0 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 40152\ntool_uses: 20\nduration_ms: 152300</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d3005709-ab89-47ca-8f40-a8619351863a","uuid":"335524fa-09dd-4ab0-9edc-0ccc84fb985d","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the changes in the last commit (git diff HEAD~1) for correctness, edge cases, and code quality. Focus on:\n1. FTS5 implementation correctness in src/db.ts\n2. Search and suggest endpoints in src/routes.ts\n3. Query sanitization safety\n4. Edge cases that might not be covered\n\nRead src/db.ts and src/routes.ts fully, then provide findings categorized as HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW priority.","agentId":"ac2a0b0","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the implementation. Let me compile my findings.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: FTS5 Full-Text Search Implementation\n\n**Commit**: `41905eb` (\"implementation\")\n**Files Reviewed**: `/workspace/src/db.ts`, `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, `/workspace/src/models.ts`, `/workspace/tests/search.test.ts`\n**Test Status**: All 35 tests passing.\n\n---\n\n### What Was Done Well\n\n- The FTS5 content-sync table pattern (`content='notes'`, `content_rowid='id'`) with insert/delete/update triggers is the canonical SQLite approach -- correctly implemented.\n- BM25 ranking and `snippet()` usage are idiomatic FTS5.\n- Parameterized queries throughout -- no raw string interpolation into SQL.\n- Inner `try/catch` blocks around FTS MATCH operations gracefully degrade invalid queries to empty results rather than 500 errors.\n- The test suite is comp