\nThe suggest sanitizer uses a simpler approach: `q.trim().replace(/[^\\w\\s]/g, '') + '*'`. This strips punctuation but preserves whitespace and alphabetic characters. Input `\"OR NOT\"` becomes `\"OR NOT*\"`, which is an FTS5 boolean expression meaning \"OR (any token starting with NOT).\" This is nonsensical and may throw or return unexpected results.\n\nSimilarly, input `\"hello world\"` becomes `\"hello world*\"`, where FTS5 interprets this as an implicit AND of `hello` and the prefix `world*`. While arguably reasonable for autocomplete, the behavior with internal whitespace creating multi-token MATCH queries may surprise users and differs from the search endpoint's semantics.\n\nRecommendation: Apply the same FTS5 keyword quoting from H1 to the suggest sanitizer, and consider taking only the last whitespace-delimited token for prefix matching.\n\n**M2: `perPage` is hardcoded with no upper-bound validation on `page`**\n\nFile: `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, lines 64-66\n\nWhile `page` is floored at 1 via `Math.max(1, ...)`, there is no upper bound. A request with `page=999999999` will compute `offset = (999999999 - 1) * 20 = 19999999960`, which SQLite will happily process (returning zero results), but it is wasted computation. More importantly, `perPage` is hardcoded to 20 with no way for the client to control it -- which is fine for now but worth noting if the API is expected to be flexible.\n\nRecommendation: Consider capping `page` at a reasonable maximum or computing it from `total`, and optionally accepting a `perPage` query parameter with min/max bounds.\n\n**M3: Two separate queries (COUNT then SELECT) for search pagination are not atomic**\n\nFile: `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, lines 73-97\n\nThe count query and the search query execute as two separate statements. If a concurrent write occurs between them (insert/delete), the `total` count can be inconsistent with the actual results returned. With `better-sqlite3` being synchronous this is less of a concern 