ers who see a result listed but no highlighted text in the snippet.\n\nRecommendation: Consider using column index `-1` to let FTS5 choose the best column for the snippet, or generate snippets for both title and body.\n\n**L3: The `<mark>` HTML tags in snippets are not escaped/sanitized for XSS if rendered client-side**\n\nFile: `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, line 88\n\nThe snippet output contains raw `<mark>` and `</mark>` tags. If the original note content contains HTML (e.g., `<script>alert(1)</script>`), that HTML will appear in the snippet output unescaped. While this is an API (not a rendered page), any frontend consuming this API must sanitize the snippet before inserting it into the DOM. This is standard practice but worth documenting in API docs.\n\n**L4: Prepared statements are created inside route handlers on every request**\n\nFile: `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, lines 73, 84, 123\n\nEach call to `db.prepare(...)` parses and compiles the SQL statement. While `better-sqlite3` is fast at this and the overhead is small, it is more idiomatic to prepare statements once at router creation time and reuse them. This is how the CRUD routes in the existing codebase also work (they do the same thing, so this is consistent with the project's pattern, just noting it as a general optimization opportunity).\n\n**L5: No test for multi-word suggest queries or suggest with FTS5 operator keywords**\n\nFile: `/workspace/tests/search.test.ts`\n\nThe test suite covers single-prefix suggest queries well but does not test edge cases like `q=OR`, `q=hello world`, or `q=*` for the suggest endpoint. Given the issues noted in M1, adding these tests would catch regressions.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| ID | Priority | Category | Description |\n|----|----------|----------|-------------|\n| H1 | HIGH | Security/Correctness | FTS5 boolean operators (NOT, OR, AND, NEAR) pass through sanitization |\n| H2 | HIGH | Correctness | Bare `*` wildcard query can match all rows or produce undefined behavior |\n| H3 | HIGH | Security | Special characters inside quoted phrases are not sanitized |\n| M1 | MEDIUM | Correctness | Suggest endpoint passes FTS5 operators through to MATCH |\n| M2 | MEDIUM | Robustness | No upper bound on `page` parameter |\n| M3 | MEDIUM | Consistency | COUNT and SELECT for pagination are not atomic |\n| M4 | MEDIUM | Maintainability | Route ordering dependency is implicit and fragile |\n| L1 | LOW | Performance | Empty-string fallback still executes a MATCH query |\n| L2 | LOW | UX | Snippet hardcoded to body column; title-only matches show no highlight |\n| L3 | LOW | Security | `<mark>` snippet output is not HTML-escaped for downstream consumers |\n| L4 | LOW | Performance | Prepared statements recreated per request |\n| L5 | LOW | Testing | Missing edge-case tests for suggest endpoint |\n\nThe three HIGH issues (H1, H2, H3) all relate to the `sanitizeFtsQuery` function in `/workspace/src/routes.ts` lines 6-26. They share a common root cause: the sanitizer was designed to strip punctuation-based FTS5 operators but does not account for keyword-based operators or content inside quoted phrases. A focused revision of that single function -- plus a parallel fix to the suggest sanitizer on line 119 -- would address all three HIGH and the M1 MEDIUM finding."}],"totalDurationMs":152300,"totalTokens":40152,"totalToolUseCount":20,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":400,"cache_read_input_tokens":36587,"output_tokens":3164,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":400,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[]}}}
